\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Did neighbours used to pop in as well casually without invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Oh yes, yes, we've - always just - been all right like, we - with any neighbours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
Did your parents ever go out to visit their friends or neighbours, visit their houses? You've already said your parents used to visit the friends they had at Howarth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Did they visit their friends at Exleigh Head?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Yes. Yes. Yes. They did. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Would they go into the houses of neighbours as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Oh - yes, it - yes well - well I think - the - what these - when - come here - a few of them, they were friendly. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 And your parents would go to their houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
Yes. Yes, just the same. The - and they kept - well, up to the - them living - all of 'em, I think they - they seemed to keep their friendships up with them, yes, they did, mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 People oft
en tell us that in those days they made their own amusements. What do you think your parents did when they got together with their friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Well I don't think they did a - a big lot, only talk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 They wouldn't have music or games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 No - well, I don't say there were any games, it'd be talking. And happen a - a drink. Or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Would someone play the piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Me mother used to make homemade wine you know, she made - used to make her own - blackberry wine, she
 used to go gathering blackberries - and - she used to make a - and - she'd happen have - some - nice wine glasses, and she - they'd have a glass of wine. But - I don't - I don't say it were - she - it weren't bought - what - she never bought wine, it wer
e
 what - but it were very good. Mm. But - as I say they - they just made - and talked, and like they didn't stay - late, so - as they do now you know, because - they'd to walk - as a rule, there wouldn't be any - say from - I can remember - being very litt
l
e walking from Haworty right - up top of Coldsahwas there. Coldshaws. On - on Sun - Sun Street there. Coldshaw. Coldshaw. Mm. You went on Sun Street there and we had to - and we walked from there - and - and and we - over Howarth, if you can come up over 
a
nd - down Tin Lane - Lord Lane, up Tin Lane, and walked - to here. And we used to be nearly asleep. Eh, and so as I say - like - those were outings you know and - they made - seemed to make 'em last for - a month or two but happen you did more visiting in
 the - light weather. When it were dark. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
Many people divide society into different social classes or groups. In that time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another? And could you tell me what the different ones were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Well - I think that there'd be - there was - do you mean in a friendly way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Say this village, there would be - perhaps different groups of people within the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 I wondered if you could sort of divide the village up your
self into the sort of - what would you describe your family as being? What sort of people were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 They were just - they were just - quiet - just quiet ordinary working people I'd call 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Would you say that within the village there was a sec
tion of people who were much poorer than your family? And if so what sort of people were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Well - there were some - poor people round Oakworth I know when I were young, but they seemed very nice, but I don't know what -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 You would call them very poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
Yes, I did - I thought there were some - were poor like, but they seem - when - they got some workers - oh they seemed to get on their feet then you know. But - when there's children little - yes, you know, it gets everybody down. Mother - 
mother gets down when they're - they're - well they do when - mother's gets down if you - if it's a bit busy like when there are two or three of 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 So you'd put yourself in the sort of ordinary working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Yes. Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Would you say that there were people in the village who were better off than you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
Well - no, well - I think there'd be - just a - just had a nice going as what me mother used to call 'em. The - I think they have a nice going on like. Well that were just - consider
ed a - not - wealthy I should say, just - nicely - and not having back - you know, because - there must have been a lot had - not enough money to - hardly to buy in with them days I'm sure. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Would you say there were any people in the village who were really very wealthy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
The - the - all of the - the - in the village - our time - if they - you always thought that same as mill owners were wealthy, that's about - I don't remember any ordinary people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 What did you used to refer to them as, these people with all the money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
We just - for - we used to say - the - Haggas's at the Manor you know - and then Haggas's at - Greenfield House up there. And - I don't know as - of course - but I was only very little when - it were Sir Isaac Holdings 
you know at the bottom - at the bottom there like well - I don't remember ought about - that lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 He would be even better off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 He would be in a different class than say the Haggas's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 He would be very very wealthy wouldn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
Yes, oh yes, yes, he would be you know, would - and I don't know of any - of course down Station Road at that time - there was Sugden's. Colonel Sugden. And they ran - they were - it were called Sugdens that time, was right - was Levous
es not long ago yes. Well that was Sugden's in my day, when - and the house - well now the houses but - I think they are flats now, well Rowses lived there. But I think it's made into flats now. Well - this at this side of the roadside - eeh what do they 
c
all that, Hamworth Drive, and there was a big house there and that was Sugden's. And that were pulled down. And these here - up the drive, Hamworth Drive - that was the road up to the house, now at that time - they had - there were Colonel Sugden and his 
w
ife, but I never saw her, she was an invalid like - a long - well they say she didn't go out, and they had four maids - at that time, a cook and - and the youngest - like - well I - I - I got to know them - oh they come - started coming to church did two 
-
 they must have been brought up church, there were four of 'em, there were a cook, I - I forget their names now but the youngest one - come to church and she got - friends - with my cousin that lives on there by himself, Wilfred Riley, he's eighty-three, 
a
nd - he got friends with - one of the maids, she were younger than him then of course, but they got - they married. Yes. Then - his parents lived at this house at top of street, me Uncle John's, and - she was servant down there, there were four of 'em but
 
- they - they changed, same - they used to change did - these here staffs, but I suppose - but she stayed all the time. And they got married and she - she were married from me mother's - from this house. Yes. Me mother let her - stop here - with me like a
n
d - well, I'm saying with me, I were married then but - when she got married but she got my room just for the - the time being. And - before then like before she was married - I went down now and again to Hamworth, he invited me down but I never saw the l
a
dy. Now when I was twenty-one - I had a cake - and we - they come up you know and had a drink and - and a - cup of tea and some of me cake, and so I sent - Mrs Sugden down - some down and - she sent me a lovely present. And I - I - and I never saw her, an
d a lovely letter. And it was a workbox. I have it now. Padded all the side with red silk a walnut one. And - I always remember that you see with - with never seeing her. Mm. And so - there were like all sorts of - of things in them days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 You said there were different classes of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
Yes, and they - they must have been wealthy. Yes, they were. I think they were - you see - that was just - I'd been friends with 'em a long while but that was when I weren twenty-one this cake, you see, and - and 
- my - cousin - her mother - well my cousin lives down - down that road. Station Road. Top. Park Avenue. Mrs Sunderland. And - but - she - she were born on the Friday, thirty-first of March and my birthday - was on the Sunday, I was twenty-one. And you se
e
 - with all - her mother and my - her mother was younger than my mother. But - we'd always - had a lot to do in common, she'd made me this cake and I went for it - on the Friday, and when I got there - there were - doctor there - and - I were - oh I come 
s
traight back, with me cake but she'd make - finished it day before. Aye. And so - Miriam - hers were called - her'll be sixty - this - month on the thirty-first. She come up last night. And - she's had her ups and downs, she come - she lived at Huxnall wh
e
n she were married. And she had a lit - a shop, a confectioner's shop, she learnt confectionery but - she sold out to come to look after her mother. Down Station Road, down Park Avenue, the same house - and then - she had one son. And - he - he grew up. B
u
t - she - she lost - she lost her husband first. She weren't so - old, about forty some. And then after - I think - I think he - and then Keith was - killed, yes. And - she's had those two - sad does in between. And so - she - come up last night, and - to
 invite us down to our - tea, for her birthday you see. I says, oh well I said, if she makes cakes you know, beautiful cakes, we - and - so - so - that's - how it comes about our - cakes but - and so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Go on about the different classes of people at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Mm. So - that's one place we've always - gone down there and she's come here you see when her mother was living as well. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 You've already told me that you would say that you belonged to the working class who were sort of comfortably off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
What sort of people belonged to the same class as yourself? What sort of jobs did the husbands and fathers do of the families who were in a similar position to your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Well - they were part you see - went - they were joiner
s you know, that seemed to go - right - there's always been a - a very nice lot of joiners in - in Oakworth like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Skilled men?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Skilled men, yes, yes, and - and their shop down there at Oakworth Hall like it - they've been plumbers for - nine ten
 - well that - house was pulled down in 1911. Well it were before then - at - a - like - well my husband were - were born down there, and he's as old as me so - they've been in trade like on - a lot of years like - at that shop, well they were - they were
 called skilled people you know. And then joiners, there were the Wilkinson\rquote s, there's some now you know. But - there were another - two generations, and they had a place up - back of the park there. I think it'd be there yet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 And they had a similar sort of going on to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Yes. And they - all - yes, brothers that brought it up and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 So what sort of people belonged to the other classes, you said there was a poorer group of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 What sort of people were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Well - I 
- I would say that they were - most of 'em were very clean. They weren't - they couldn't - be - dress happen as they would have liked but they - as they got working - workers coming on they seemed to improve. But I think that - I don't know whether at the
se firms advertised for families or not, in those days. They seemed to come with families, poor families, and there were two or three years before they - seemed to get onto their feet, but I don't remember - any of 'em being right - bad. Bad people.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 They were just poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Poor, yes. But they seemed to get onto their feet.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 They were poor because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
Oh but they got the - you know, there just seemed to be a few - poor families, but - now they always called the other end the better end. Yes. Up - up Lidget. Up better end.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
So you're not saying that these poor families were poor because of the job that the father did, it was more because of the size of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Yes. I - I think some of 'em, same as the Haggas's - some come with fam
ilies - that had their - like - the father - had - looked after horses, and with the wagons. Well, there were two or three lots come like that, but - to look after - so they could cart - they had to cart their own stuff from station, to the mill. And - an
d
 they - had their own carts, now these families, some of 'em, I know two or three - that come - from off somewhere, see they happen - they used tom - call it more - the coal - where they were - mining districts and suchlike used to say, well they did that
 - at Hattersley\rquote s you know. They were workers and they brought their families and they got - got on with the - same as - some of - at - at Hattersley\rquote 
s, I think there'd be - same as joiners, and - and were - and blacksmiths, things like that you - they - l
ots have come round here, like men have got - the - when - got onto their feet you see and they've seemed poor when they were come. But they've - been some workers in the families - yes they have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 You already said that the class that were better off than you were the mill owners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
Yes, yes, I think - I think those - what - mill owners were - all class that - what you could call better end. Yes, but - what they used to call the better end. Mm. And I daresay they were - like - if any functions or an
ything like that I daresay they had - they'd give. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another? Were you ever taught to treat people from the better end -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 You weren't taught to treat them any differently than the poor people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 
No, no, no, no, if - if we did happen to - it were just - were brought up - like to talk to 'em - and just - speak when you're spoken to. Not be rude.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8918414 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 Were you ever told to curtsey or show respect in some way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2256154 ES  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16649235\charrsid11482206 No, I don't think so.
